在學生的種族分布方面，在美國所有大學之中，黑人大學生從此類大學畢業的比率持續下降，從1976年的35%下降到2001年的21.5%<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nces.ed.gov/pubs2004/2004062.pdf|title=Historically Black Colleges and Universities,1976 to 2001|page=4|work=Dept. of Education|date=September 2004|accessdate=2010-01-19|archive-date=2020-10-21|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201021025806/https://nces.ed.gov/pubs2004/2004062.pdf|dead-url=no}}</ref>，但奇怪的是，這些大學的收生人數卻有增無減，從1976年的18萬上升到2001年的22萬，而其中大部分的增長是由於黑人女學生的入學人數，由8萬8千人上升到約38萬人<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nces.ed.gov/pubs2004/2004062.pdf|title=Historically Black Colleges and Universities,1976 to 2001|page=31|work=Dept. of Education|date=September 2004|accessdate=2010-01-19|archive-date=2020-10-21|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201021025806/https://nces.ed.gov/pubs2004/2004062.pdf|dead-url=no}}</ref>。<!---

In 1975, Jake Ayers Sr. filed a lawsuit against [[Mississippi|Mississippi]] for giving more financial support to its predominantly white public colleges. The state settled the lawsuit in 2002 and agreed to direct $503 million to three historically black colleges, collectively, over 17 years.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.taragana.com/politics/2009/11/19/opposition-strong-to-barbours-plan-to-merge-mississippis-3-black-universities-into-1-795/|title=Opposition strong to Barbour’s plan to merge Mississippi’s 3 black universities into 1|date=November 19, 2009|work=Associated Press|accessdate=2010-01-21}}</ref>

Following the enactment of [[Civil_Rights_Act_of_1964|Civil Rights laws]] in the 1960s, all educational institutions that receive federal funding have undertaken [[affirmative_action|affirmative action]] to increase their racial diversity. Some historically black colleges now have non-black majorities, notably [[West_Virginia_State_University|West Virginia State University]] and [[Bluefield_State_College|Bluefield State College]] whose student body has been roughly 90% [[White_American|white]] since the mid-1960s. Many non-state-supported HBCUs are struggling financially, due to the increased cost of delivering private education to students and declining financial aid for students.<ref name=cnn1>{{cite news|last=Endo|first=Sandra |url=http://www.cnn.com/video/#/video/business/2009/08/12/endo.black.colleges.struggle.cnn|title=Black colleges struggling|publisher=CNN|date=August 12, 2009|accessdate=August 13, 2009}}</ref> As colleges work harder to maintain enrollment levels, the percentage of non-African American enrollment has tended to climb. The following table highlights HBCUs with high non-African American enrollments:
